2026-04-21 01:34:18 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['Power supply internal wiring (connection of input socket to PCB and to green LED)', 'Control module red LED polarity / wiring (control indicator circuit)'] hypothesis_explanation='From the tests: 12 V is present at the power supply input socket, but at the module outputs the conductor labeled (+) sits at about −12 V with respect to ground, and the conductor labeled (−) sits at about 0 V. Thus, relative to the external reference, the supply is wired with its polarity reversed internally: the socket’s positive pin is effectively tied to the module’s output that is marked (−/0 V), while the socket’s negative pin is tied to the module’s output that is marked (+/12 V). This explains why the control-module ‘inverted cables’ red LED is lit (it sees the control-module 12 V and 0 V lines reversed relative to expectation) and why the main lamp does not turn on (the series diode in the load module is reverse‑biased when the external cables are reversed).\n\nThe persistent behavior with the control switch open/closed, and the fact that the power‑supply green LED remains off even though 12 V is at the input socket, is also consistent with the internal polarity in the power-supply cube being swapped with respect to the LED orientation and to the outgoing leads. Therefore the fault is most likely a configuration/wiring error inside the power supply module: the two conductors from the DC input jack have been connected to the wrong pads/rails, so the designated output leads are reversed relative to the LED and internal schematic.\n\nTo fix, the technician should correct the internal wiring of the power supply module so that the output cable intended to be +12 V is connected to the jack’s positive terminal (and to the LED’s anode via its series resistor), and the output cable intended to be 0 V is connected to the jack’s negative terminal. After correction, the green LED should light with 12 V applied, the red ‘inverted cables’ indicator in the control module should stay off in normal operation, and the lamp should illuminate when the switch is closed.'
