2026-04-21 01:34:38 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['Polarity of connection between power supply module outputs and control module inputs (PSU Output Cable (+) connected to Control Input (−), and PSU Output Cable (−) connected to Control Input (+))', 'Polarity of connection between control module outputs and load module inputs (Control Output Cable (+) connected to Load Input (−), and Control Output Cable (−) connected to Load Input (+))'] hypothesis_explanation='All component‑level tests show the three modules are internally healthy and correctly wired: the PSU provides 12 V (though its labeled (+) lead sits at −12 V versus ground), the control module simply passes that polarity through, its red indicator correctly lights when the upstream polarity is inverted relative to its expected convention, and the load module diode and lamps have normal continuity and correct internal polarity.\n\nThe only remaining fault consistent with all observations is a configuration error in how the unmarked inter‑module cables are mated. Because the cables are identical and reversible, the PSU output pair has been plugged into the control‑module input pair with reversed polarity, and the control‑module output pair has likewise been plugged into the load‑module input pair with reversed polarity. This produces:\n- PSU output labeled (+) at −12 V and labeled (−) at 0 V vs ground.\n- Control module therefore sees its expected 0 V on the node it believes should be +12 V and vice versa, so its inverted‑cables indicator (red LED) turns on.\n- The same inverted polarity is delivered to the load module; its series diode is reverse‑biased, blocking current, so neither the main lamp nor the internal indicator lamp can light.\n- The PSU green LED remains off because its internal reference for polarity is now opposite to how the external socket is being used.\n\nCorrecting the fault requires re‑plugging the fast‐connection terminals so that the PSU positive output actually feeds the control‑module positive input, and likewise the control‑module positive output feeds the load‑module positive input, with the corresponding negative/return leads matched. This configuration error, not a failed component, is the root cause of the symptoms.'
