2026-04-21 01:34:59 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['Marking / identification of PSU Output Cable (+) vs PSU Output Cable (−) on the power supply module documentation / build'] hypothesis_explanation='All electrical components and inter‑module wirings have tested nominal. The PSU produces a 12 V differential between its two output leads, and continuity checks show the control and load modules expect a given polarity and are correctly wired internally. However, the multimeter tests reveal that the lead labeled/assumed as PSU Output Cable (+) is actually the negative (0 V) node, and the lead labeled/assumed as PSU Output Cable (−) is in fact at −12 V relative to that node. The control module and load module have been connected under the assumption that the cable marked (+) was the positive 12 V supply. Because the true polarity of the PSU outputs is reversed relative to their markings/documentation, the system is operated with inverted polarity at the control and load modules: the power‑supply indicator LED (wired for correct +12 V) never forward‑biases, so it is off; the control module’s reverse‑polarity indicator LED is forward‑biased, so it is on; and the load module’s series diode (oriented to pass current only when the upstream node is actually +12 V) is reverse‑biased, so neither the main lamp nor the internal indicator can conduct, and the lamp never turns on. The root cause is therefore a design/build error in the *identification* of the PSU output cables: the cable labeled/treated as (+) is physically connected to the negative side of the supply, and the cable labeled/treated as (−) is physically connected to the positive side, even though the PSU internal circuit functions normally. Correcting this mis‑identification (swapping the functional roles of the two PSU output leads so that the truly positive lead is used as +12 V in the rest of the system) will restore correct operation without changing any other module.'
